# Footprinting a Website Using Maltego

## Course  
CYB/560 – MS Cybersecurity Capstone

## Objective  
This lab demonstrates how to use Maltego to gather open source intelligence (OSINT) on a target organization. The purpose is to visualize and analyze the target's online footprint, discover related domains, subdomains, email addresses, and other publicly available metadata.

## Tools Used  
- Maltego Community Edition  
- Internet connectivity  
- Target domain (e.g., example.com)

## Procedure  
- Launch Maltego and select “Personal” or “Company” entity type  
- Input the domain name (e.g., `example.com`) into the graph canvas  
- Right-click and run “All Transforms”  
- Observe related DNS records, associated emails, subdomains, and metadata  
- Use filters to isolate entity types (e.g., DNS Name, Netblock, Website)  
- Expand relevant entities to explore second-degree relationships  
- Save graph and export as PDF or .mtgx for reporting

## Results  
- Maltego graph revealed:
  - 3 subdomains including `dev.example.com` and `mail.example.com`  
  - 2 email addresses tied to technical personnel  
  - DNS records including A, MX, and SOA  
- No immediate vulnerabilities discovered, but intel was rich enough to support further reconnaissance

## Lessons Learned  
- Maltego provides a powerful interface for visualizing open-source data  
- OSINT tools can passively uncover valuable details without alerting the target  
- Ethical guidelines must be followed to avoid misuse or overcollection  
- Footprinting is a critical early phase in both red teaming and defensive risk assessments
